#X text 271 412 This is a low random frequency modulation at 0.5 hertz \, but we'll see now what happens when we have higher frequencies now and what happens to a single oscillator., f 44;
#X text 51 245 We've had examples in the Additive synthesis chapter where the amplitude of partials were randomly modulated. Let's look at something like that again with a multichannel oscillator (where each signal is a partial)., f 38;
#X text 271 480 When we modulate the amplitude of any signal (called the "carrier" signal) \, we simply multiplying it by any oscillating signal (called "modulator" signal). The modulating signal is usually an oscillator \, whose frequency is the modulating frequency. Check to the right and above., f 44;
